## What to do

This is a `plan`-route Premise. The deliverable lives in the tracker, not in code, not in a separate spec doc. It is a set of child Assignments that decompose this work into pieces that can each be realized, together with the Depend edges between them. Files in `docs/spec/` in the consuming repo describe what *is*; the design of work that hasn't shipped yet does not belong there.

A plan route is a conversation before it is a decomposition. Scoping is the work the author deferred, so the shape of the children is settled with the operator, in chat, while it is still forming, not read out of the code and handed over finished. Bring the operator the framing early, while it can still be pressed on; a finished design on turn one is the one outcome this route exists to prevent.

1. Claim: `vv assignment-claim {{ assignment_id }}`.
2. Read enough to orient: the code, the doctrine, any open Assignments that touch the same area, anything the operator has already said. Plan routes are exactly where the original author's framing is most likely incomplete, because scoping is what the author was deferring, so read to find what the framing got wrong, not to settle the design. Reading the code fixes your technical picture, but it can't recover what the operator meant the scope to be; that lives with them.
3. Open the scope with the operator before going further, and for this turn be the operator reading it, not the agent who did the work: you are running ten to twenty assignments like this one at once, each competing for your zero-sum attention, and you have seconds for this one before the next is waiting. You scan the bold lead of each item and read into the body under it only when a lead stops you, so the whole of what you must weigh has to live in the leads. Open by naming what this work is: the goal it decomposes, in the domain's own words as if to someone who has never seen it, before any finding. A scoping question lands on no one who does not yet hold what work it is scoping. Then draft the rest as what you would want handed to you, and read it back from that seat and cut every line that would not change how you steer the scope, every line there only to show you the work got done. Keep what you cannot act without: the corrected framing, the scoping questions the author left open, and your hot take on the shape the decomposition might take — each led, in the bold opening of its line, by the framing it corrects or the question it poses, never by the ground beneath it, which follows after in a line at most. Then black out all but those bold openings and read what is left: a question or correction that would steer the scope and is not there has not reached the operator, and you lift it into the opening rather than add a line to point at it. Don't form the full design or reach for `/decompose` until the shape is agreed between you. Then wait.
4. Once the shape is agreed, form the design from what the conversation settled: what each child realizes, the boundary with adjacent work, and the Depend edges among them.
5. Run `/decompose`. It cuts the design into the child Assignments that realize it: pressure-testing each candidate against the Bob who would pick it up, surfacing the proposed set and its dependency graph for the operator's blessing, and authoring the children in dependency order once they approve.
6. Close this Premise with `/closeout delivered`; the synopsis comment should name the child Assignment ids and the dependency graph among them.

There is typically no PR for a `plan`-route Premise; the tracker mutations are the intended artefact.

